      devanagari: 'यः शास्त्रविधिमुत्सृज्य वर्तते कामकारतः ।\nन स सिद्धिमवाप्नोति न सुखं न परां गतिम् ॥',
      transliteration: 'yaḥ śāstra-vidhim utsṛjya vartate kāma-kārataḥ\nna sa siddhim avāpnoti na sukhaṁ na parāṁ gatim',
      translation: 'One who abandons the ordinance of scripture and acts from the impulse of desire alone attains neither perfection, nor happiness, nor the supreme destination.',
      words: [
        { word: 'yaḥ śāstra-vidhim utsṛjya', meaning: 'one who abandons the ordinance of scripture / who throws aside the guidance of the teaching' },
        { word: 'vartate kāma-kārataḥ', meaning: 'acts from the impulse of desire / functions according to the force of craving' },
        { word: 'na saḥ siddhim avāpnoti', meaning: 'does not attain perfection / achieves no real accomplishment' },
        { word: 'na sukham na parāṁ gatim', meaning: 'neither happiness nor the supreme destination / no real joy and no liberation' }
      ],
      commentary: `After describing freedom from the three gates as the path to the supreme, the chapter raises the question implicit in verse 22: but how does a person know what acts for the genuine good of the self? How does one navigate without the inner vision of the fully awakened? The answer here: śāstra-vidhi — the ordinance of scripture. Not as external control but as the recorded wisdom of those who have already made the journey.\n\nKāma-kārataḥ — from the impulse of desire alone. The word kārataḥ suggests the force or compulsion of desire. The person who has no inner authority except their own desires will inevitably rationalize whatever those desires want. "I want this, therefore it must be right" — or in more sophisticated form: "I have thought about this deeply and my considered view is that what I want is actually the ethical thing." The scriptures exist to provide an external reference that desire cannot so easily corrupt.\n\nNa siddhim, na sukham, na parāṁ gatim — no perfection, no happiness, no supreme destination. Three negatives — the triple absence of everything worth having. This is the consequence not of a single wrong action but of the systematic abandonment of dharmic guidance in favor of desire. The teaching is not restrictive; it is protective. The śāstra is offered as a support for those who have not yet developed the inner compass to navigate without it.`
