      commentary: `The chapter closes with a teaching on authority — not the authority of desire, not the authority of tradition followed blindly, but the authority of śāstra: the accumulated wisdom of those who have inquired deeply and reported what they found. Pramāṇam — a measure, a standard, a source of reliable knowledge. Scripture is here placed as the pramāṇa for ethical and practical guidance.\n\nThis does not mean the Gita endorses uncritical adherence to any text. The Gita itself is śāstra, and its entire teaching is toward developing the inner wisdom that eventually renders external authority unnecessary. But for the person who is still in the early or middle stages of the journey — who has genuine desires that cloud judgment, who has not yet developed the inner compass of viveka (discrimination) — the śāstra provides an external reference that desire cannot so easily manipulate.\n\nKartum ihārhasi — you are entitled to act here. The closing word is permission, not burden. The chapter that began with a vision of divine qualities and ended with warnings about demonic trajectories closes not with threat but with invitation: you know the śāstra, you are born to the divine endowment — act. The authority of the teaching is not meant to constrain but to orient. Act from that orientation, toward the divine endowment that is your birthright, away from the three gates that would take you in the wrong direction.`
